.TH SPEEKIFY 1 "May 2026" "Speekify" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
speekify \- convert inline text, stdin, or readable URL content into a local WAV file
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B speekify
[
.I OPTIONS
]
[
.I SOURCE ...
]
.PP
.B speekify
.B setup
[
.I OPTIONS
]
.PP
.B speekify
.B inspect
[
.I OPTIONS
]
[
.I SOURCE ...
]
.PP
.B speekify
.B feed
.B rebuild|validate
[
.I OPTIONS
]
.PP
.B speekify-mcp
[
.I OPTIONS
]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Speekify is a Python CLI that turns inline text, piped stdin, or the readable body of a URL into a local WAV file generated with Supertonic v3.
.PP
The default workflow accepts plain text, piped text, or a single URL. URL input is reduced to readable article content before synthesis. English input can be translated to French before text to speech, and sparse speech tags can be added before generation.
.PP
Use
.B speekify setup
to pre-download and warm the local AI models.
Use
.B speekify --doctor
to verify the runtime dependencies, confirm that the AI models load correctly, and get a remediation hint when setup is required.
.PP
Use
.B speekify inspect
or
.B speekify --dry-run
to preview extraction, translation, speech tags, and planned output paths without running synthesis.
Use
.B speekify feed rebuild
and
.B speekify feed validate
to manage the local podcast RSS feed created from JSON sidecars.
.PP
Use
.B speekify-mcp
to expose Speekify as a local Model Context Protocol server for AI assistants that need to generate WAV files from text, URL content, or summarized news recaps.
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
.I SOURCE
Text to synthesize or a single URL to extract. Omit it only when text is piped on stdin.
.SH MAIN OPTIONS
.TP
.B --url
Force URL extraction mode even if the source looks like plain text.
.TP
.B --title
Override the output file name without the extension.
.TP
.B --voice
Select a Supertonic voice from M1-M5 or F1-F5.
.TP
.B --custom-style-path
Use a Supertonic voice-style JSON file. This overrides
.BR --voice .
.TP
.B --lang
Select the Supertonic ISO 639-1 language code such as en, fr, ja, or na.
.TP
.B --speed
Adjust the playback speed multiplier.
.TP
.B --steps
Set the synthesis step count.
.TP
.B --max-chunk-length
Set the maximum internal Supertonic chunk length.
.TP
.B --silence-duration
Set the silence inserted between Supertonic chunks.
.TP
.B --output-dir
Write the generated WAV file into a specific directory.
.TP
.B --feed-base-url
Set the public HTTP(S) directory URL used for RSS enclosure URLs.
.TP
.B --dry-run
Inspect the generation plan without creating audio.
.TP
.B --tags / --no-tags
Enable or disable sparse inline speech tags.
.TP
.B --tag-sentiment / --no-tag-sentiment
Enable or disable CardiffNLP sentiment-assisted tagging.
.TP
.B --tag-sigh / --no-tag-sigh
Enable or disable rare sigh tags.
.TP
.B --verbose
Show technical diagnostics such as the log file path.
.TP
.B --version
.TP
.B -v
Print the installed Speekify version and exit.
.TP
.B --doctor
Run installation diagnostics, verify runtime dependencies, attempt to load the AI models, and suggest
.B speekify setup
when repair or download is required.
.TP
.B -h
.TP
.B --help
Show the command help and exit.
.SH SETUP OPTIONS
.TP
.B --skip-translation
Do not warm up the English to French translation model.
.TP
.B --skip-sentiment
Do not warm up the CardiffNLP emotion and sentiment model.
.TP
.B --verbose
Show technical diagnostics such as the log file path.
.TP
.B -h
.TP
.B --help
Show setup help and exit.
.SH INSPECT AND FEED OPTIONS
.TP
.B speekify inspect
Accepts the same source, URL, language, voice, chunking, tagging, and output options as the main generation command, but does not synthesize or write a WAV file.
.TP
.B speekify feed rebuild --output-dir DIR
Rebuild
.I speekify-feed.xml
from JSON sidecars in the output directory.
.TP
.B speekify feed validate --output-dir DIR
Validate feed inputs by checking JSON sidecars and referenced WAV files.
.TP
.B --feed-base-url
Override the public enclosure base URL while rebuilding the feed.
.SH MCP SERVER
The
.B speekify-mcp
entry point runs an MCP server over stdio by default. It exposes the
.B speekify_generate_wav
tool for converting inline text or readable URL content into a WAV file,
.B speekify_generation_defaults
for supported voices and language defaults, and a
.B news_recap_to_audio
prompt for source-summary-to-audio automations.
.PP
The generation tool accepts CLI-equivalent controls including feed base URL, English-island handling, custom English lexicon path, and optional user-config defaults.
.TP
.B --transport
Select the MCP transport, either stdio or streamable-http.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B speekify "Hello world"
Generate a WAV file from inline text.
.TP
.B speekify --lang fr "Hello world"
Generate French speech.
.TP
.B speekify https://example.com/article
Extract readable article text and synthesize it.
.TP
.B printf 'Hello from stdin' | speekify
Read the text from standard input.
.TP
.B speekify --doctor
Check dependencies, model availability, and installation health.
.TP
.B speekify --dry-run https://example.com/article
Preview URL extraction and planned audio paths without synthesis.
.TP
.B speekify inspect "Hello world"
Inspect inline text generation without creating a WAV file.
.TP
.B speekify feed rebuild --output-dir ~/Speekify/audio
Rebuild the RSS feed from existing JSON sidecars.
.TP
.B speekify feed validate --output-dir ~/Speekify/audio
Validate sidecars and audio references for the feed.
.TP
.B speekify setup
Download and warm the local AI models.
.TP
.B speekify-mcp
Run the MCP server for local AI clients over stdio.
.TP
.B speekify-mcp --transport streamable-http
Run the MCP server with streamable HTTP transport for local experiments.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I logs/speekify.log
Runtime log file maintained automatically by the CLI.
.TP
.I ~/.config/speekify/config.toml
Optional TOML file for generation defaults. Set
.B SPEEKIFY_CONFIG
to use another config path. Explicit CLI options override config values.
.TP
.I speekify-feed.xml
Podcast-style RSS feed refreshed in each output directory.
.SH EXIT STATUS
The command exits with status 0 on success and non-zero on failure. The
.B --doctor
command exits non-zero when dependencies are missing or when one of the models cannot be loaded.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR man (1)